const FCO_KNOWLEDGE_BASE = "Mastering Claude | First Class Operations\nFirst Class Operations \u00b7 AI Mastery Series\nStop Wasting Time on the\nWrong AI.\nMaster Claude.\nThe definitive playbook for business leaders and operators who want to turn Claude into their most productive team member \u2014 not just another chatbot.\nStart the Masterclass \u2192\n\u26a1 Build My Files Now\n6\nCore Tools Covered\n30\nMinutes to Implement\n10\u00d7\nOutput Multiplier\n$0\nExtra Cost Beyond Pro\n\u2699 The Shift\nClaude Is Not One Tool. It Is Six.\nMost people open Claude, type a question, and get a generic answer. That is not how operators use it. In 2026, Claude is a complete AI workspace \u2014 and the gap between those who know this and those who don't is enormous.\n\ud83d\udda5\nTool 01\nClaude Cowork\nA desktop app that reads your actual files, builds documents, and asks clarifying questions instead of guessing.\nMost Important\n\ud83e\udde0\nTool 02\nThe Right Model\nOpus 4.6 with Extended Thinking. Forces Claude to reason before responding \u2014 like a senior advisor, not an intern.\nCritical Setting\n\ud83d\udcca\nTool 03\nClaude in Excel\nAn add-in that lives inside your spreadsheet. It reads formulas, builds financial models, and explains cell logic.\nFinance & Ops\n\ud83d\udd0c\nTool 04\nClaude Plugins\nPre-built skill packs for Sales, Marketing, Legal, Data, and more. Instant expertise with slash commands.\nSpecialisation\n\u26a1\nTool 05\nClaude Artifacts\nInteractive outputs \u2014 calculators, dashboards, trackers \u2014 built live inside the chat. Not text. Working tools.\nInteractive Output\n\ud83d\udcc1\nTool 06\nClaude Projects\nPersistent context folders where Claude remembers your brand guidelines, past work, and specific data.\nMemory & Context\n\u2699 Deep Dives\nEach Tool, Explained for Operators\nClick any tool below to expand the full setup guide, use cases, and first prompts. Start with Cowork \u2014 it is the foundation everything else is built on.\n1\nClaude Cowork\nYour desktop AI co-pilot that reads your files and aligns before executing\n\u25be\nClaude Cowork is the single most important upgrade you can make. It lives on your computer, reads your actual files, and \u2014 crucially \u2014 asks you clarifying questions before it starts working. This alone eliminates 80% of the frustration people have with AI.\n\ud83d\udca1\nThe Mindset Shift:\nChatGPT trained you to write better prompts. Claude Cowork makes that obsolete. The game is now\ncontext files\n. Feed Claude great information upfront, and you stop prompting entirely.\nHow to Install (5 Minutes)\nGo to\nclaude.com/download\nand download the desktop app.\nYou need a\nPro account ($20/month)\nor $17/month billed annually.\nOpen the app and click the\nCowork tab\nat the top.\nSelect a folder from your computer \u2014 this is how Claude reads your files.\nCreate your first\ncontext .md file\n(see the Context Files section below).\nThe Alignment Prompt (Use This Every Time)\n\ud83d\udccb First Prompt Template\nCopy\nI want to [YOUR TASK] so that [WHAT SUCCESS LOOKS LIKE].\nFirst, read the uploaded files completely before responding.\nDO NOT start executing yet. Instead, ask me clarifying questions \nso we can refine the approach together step by step.\nOnly begin work once we've aligned on the direction.\n\ud83c\udfaf\nWhy this works:\nClaude generates a form that forces you to be specific. If the direction is wrong, say so \u2014 Claude will generate a new form. With a 1,000,000 token context window, it never loses track of the conversation.\nReal Business Use Cases\n\ud83d\udcdd\nSOPs & Process Documentation\nFeed Claude your existing process notes and have it build a complete, formatted SOP document with decision trees.\n\"Read my notes on the client onboarding process and build a full SOP with a decision tree for edge cases. Ask me questions first.\"\n\ud83d\udcc8\nQuarterly Business Reviews\nUpload your raw data files and have Claude synthesise them into a structured executive presentation narrative.\n\"Read the Q3 data files and draft a QBR narrative for the leadership team. Highlight the 3 biggest wins and 2 critical risks.\"\n\ud83e\udd1d\nProposal & Pitch Writing\nUpload your brand guidelines, past proposals, and the client brief \u2014 Claude writes a proposal that sounds like you.\n\"Using my brand voice file and the client brief, write a proposal for this project. Match my tone exactly. Ask clarifying questions first.\"\n\ud83d\udd0d\nCompetitive Intelligence\nFeed Claude competitor data, market reports, and your positioning doc to get a strategic gap analysis.\n\"Analyse these competitor profiles against our positioning. Identify our 3 strongest differentiators and 2 areas of vulnerability.\"\n2\nUse the Right Model\nOpus 4.6 + Extended Thinking \u2014 the senior advisor setting\n\u25be\nMost people use the default model and wonder why the output feels shallow. The model you choose is the difference between a junior assistant and a senior strategist. Right now, the correct choice is Opus 4.6 with Extended Thinking enabled.\nHow to Set It Up\nOpen any Claude chat on\nclaude.ai\nor in Cowork.\nClick the\nmodel selector dropdown\nat the bottom of the chat.\nSelect\nOpus 4.6\n.\nToggle on\nExtended Thinking\n\u2014 this is the critical step most people miss.\n\ud83e\udde0\nWhat Extended Thinking does:\nIt forces Claude to reason through a problem internally before responding \u2014 like a consultant who thinks before they speak. For strategic decisions, financial analysis, and complex writing, the quality difference is dramatic.\nConnecting Your Tools\nClaude can connect directly to Slack, Google Drive, Notion, Figma, and 50+ other tools via Connectors. Once connected, Claude searches your actual data \u2014 no copy-pasting, no screenshots.\nGo to\nSettings \u2192 Connectors\nin Claude.\nBrowse the directory and click\nAdd\non the tools you use.\nNow ask Claude to search your Slack messages or pull from your Google Docs mid-conversation.\n\u26a0\ufe0f\nWhen to use a faster model:\nFor quick drafts, simple formatting, or repetitive tasks, switch to a lighter model to preserve your usage limits. Save Opus 4.6 for strategic and complex work.\n3\nClaude in Excel\nAI that lives inside your spreadsheet and understands every cell\n\u25be\nEvery other AI flattens your spreadsheet into text and loses the formulas. Claude in Excel is different \u2014 it lives inside the workbook, reads every tab, and knows what each cell actually contains. This is the tool that changes how you build financial models.\nInstallation (3 Minutes)\nOpen\nMicrosoft Excel\n(desktop or web, 2016 or later).\nGo to\nInsert \u2192 Get Add-ins\n(Windows) or\nTools \u2192 Add-ins\n(Mac).\nSearch\n\"Claude by Anthropic\"\nand click Add.\nSign in with your Claude account (Pro plan required).\nPress\nCtrl+Option+C\n(Mac) or find the Claude icon in your ribbon.\nHigh-Value Prompts for Operators\n\ud83d\udcca Excel Prompts\nCopy\n\"Give me a plain-English summary of what each tab in this workbook does.\"\n\"Find all #REF and #VALUE errors and explain what is causing each one.\"\n\"Build a 3-year P&L model for a service business with 40% gross margins. \nUse formulas, not hardcoded numbers. Put assumptions in their own tab.\"\n\"Create a client retention dashboard: churn rate, LTV, \ncohort analysis, and a 6-month forecast.\"\n\"Convert this flat data table into a pivot summary \ngrouped by month and product category.\"\nBuild a Financial Model from Scratch\n\ud83d\udcbc Full Model Prompt\nCopy\nCreate a professional Excel spreadsheet (.xlsx) for: [PURPOSE]\nContext: [WHO IS IT FOR AND HOW WILL IT BE USED]\nIt should cover: [LIST WHAT YOU WANT TO TRACK OR CALCULATE]\nRules:\n- Use Excel formulas (SUM, SUMIF, IF, VLOOKUP) \u2014 never hardcoded calculations\n- Put all editable assumptions in a clearly labelled \"Inputs\" tab\n- Blue text for inputs, black for formula-driven cells\n- Freeze top row, auto-fit columns\n- Include a dashboard tab with key metrics and a trend chart\n4\nClaude Plugins\nInstant specialist expertise with one click\n\u25be\nAnthropic released official plugins for Sales, Marketing, Legal, Finance, Data Analysis, Product Management, and Customer Support. Each one gives Claude specific workflows, domain knowledge, and slash commands for that function. You do not need to be technical. You just click install.\nHow to Install\nOpen\nClaude Cowork\n.\nGo to\nclaude.com/plugins\nand browse the directory.\nClick\nInstall\non the plugin that matches your role.\nIn any chat, type\n/\nto see all available slash commands.\nPlugin Use Cases by Role\n\ud83d\udce3\nMarketing Plugin\nDraft content, build campaign briefs, and create audience-specific messaging \u2014 all with your voice profile loaded.\n/draft-content Write a LinkedIn post about [topic]. Use my uploaded voice profile. Target [audience]. Goal: newsletter signups.\n\ud83d\udcbc\nSales Plugin\nResearch accounts, prepare for calls, draft outreach sequences, and build competitive battlecards automatically.\n/research-account Analyse [Company Name]. Find their recent news, key decision makers, and likely pain points for our solution.\n\ud83d\udcc9\nData Plugin\nExplore datasets, write SQL queries, build interactive dashboards, and validate your analysis \u2014 no data science background needed.\n/build-dashboard Create an interactive dashboard from this CSV. Include filters by date and category. Show trends over time.\n\u2696\ufe0f\nLegal Plugin\nReview contracts, flag unusual clauses, summarise legal documents, and draft standard agreements for review.\n/review-contract Review this service agreement. Flag any unusual liability clauses, payment terms, or IP ownership issues.\n5\nClaude Artifacts\nWorking tools built inside the chat \u2014 not just text\n\u25be\nArtifacts are the most underused feature in Claude. Instead of giving you text that describes a calculator, Claude builds the actual calculator. Interactive HTML, visual charts, project trackers, and org charts \u2014 all live inside the chat window, ready to download and use.\n\u26a1\nNo setup required.\nArtifacts work automatically in Claude Cowork and on claude.ai. Just ask for something interactive and Claude builds it.\nHigh-Impact Artifact Prompts\n\u26a1 Artifact Prompts\nCopy\n\"Create an interactive ROI calculator for a SaaS product. \nInputs: monthly cost, hours saved per week, hourly rate. \nShow payback period and annual ROI. Clean, professional design.\"\n\"Build a visual comparison chart of our three service tiers \nwith a feature matrix and a recommended tier highlight.\"\n\"Create a project tracker with columns for Task, Owner, \nStatus (dropdown), Priority, and Due Date. Include a progress bar.\"\n\"Build an interactive org chart for a 15-person operations team. \nMake it collapsible by department.\"\n\"Create a weekly capacity planner with team member rows, \nproject columns, and colour-coded utilisation (green/amber/red).\"\n6\nClaude Projects\nPersistent memory folders for ongoing work\n\u25be\nProjects give Claude a persistent memory for a specific body of work. Upload your brand docs, writing samples, and reference material once \u2014 and every conversation in that project has access to them. Best used for ongoing client work, newsletter production, or recurring reporting.\nSetup in 5 Minutes\nGo to\nclaude.ai\nand click\nProjects\nin the left sidebar.\nClick\nCreate Project\nand give it a clear name (e.g., \"Q2 Client Reporting\").\nClick\nAdd Content\nand upload your key files: brand docs, past examples, data.\nStart a new conversation \u2014 Claude now has full context from your uploaded files.\n\u26a0\ufe0f\nFCO Recommendation:\nFor most operators,\nCowork + markdown files\nis more reliable and flexible than Projects. Use Projects for client-specific work where you want a clean, isolated context. Use Cowork for your day-to-day operations workflow.\n\ud83d\udcc4 The New Game\nStop Prompting. Start Building Context Files.\nThe biggest unlock in Claude is not a better prompt. It is a better context file. When you give Claude rich, structured information about your business upfront, you stop prompting entirely \u2014 and start getting outputs that sound like your best work.\n\ud83d\udc64\nAbout Me / My Business\nYour role, goals, communication style, and examples of your best work. This is the foundation file every operator needs.\nabout.md\n\ud83c\udfa8\nBrand Guidelines\nYour tone of voice, words you use, words you avoid, target audience, and core values. Ensures every output is on-brand.\nbrand.md\n\ud83d\udccb\nWorkflow / Process\nStep-by-step instructions for how a specific task should be completed. Claude follows your process, not a generic one.\nworkflow_[name].md\n\ud83d\udcca\nData & Reference\nKey metrics, pricing tables, product specs, or any reference data Claude should have access to for accurate outputs.\nreference_data.md\n\u270d\ufe0f\nWriting Samples\nYour best emails, proposals, or reports. Claude learns your style from examples, not descriptions.\nwriting_samples.md\n\ud83c\udfaf\nClient / Audience Profiles\nDetailed profiles of your key clients or target audiences. Claude tailors every output to the right reader.\naudience_profiles.md\nSee Inside a Real Context File\nClick the tabs to explore what each file type looks like in practice.\nabout.md\nbrand.md\nworkflow_proposal.md\naudience_profiles.md\n# About Me \u2014 [Your Name]\n## Role & Context\nRole:\nFounder & Managing Director, First Class Operations\nIndustry:\nBusiness Operations Consulting\nTeam Size:\n12 people across operations, delivery, and growth\n## What I Do\nI help founder-led businesses build the operational infrastructure \nthey need to scale without chaos. My clients are typically \n\u00a31M\u2013\u00a310M revenue businesses that have outgrown their current \nsystems and need a professional operations layer.\n## Communication Style\nTone:\nDirect, confident, no fluff. I respect people's time.\nFormat:\nShort paragraphs. Clear headers. Bullet points only when listing.\nAvoid:\nJargon, passive voice, filler phrases like \"it's worth noting\"\nSignature phrases:\n\"First class execution\", \"operational clarity\", \"built to scale\"\n## My Goals This Quarter\n1. Close 3 new retainer clients at \u00a35K/month\n2. Launch the FCO AI Masterclass programme\n3. Reduce delivery overhead by 20% through better SOPs\n## Example of Writing I'm Proud Of\n[Paste your best email, proposal intro, or LinkedIn post here]\n# First Class Operations \u2014 Brand Guidelines\n## Brand Positioning\nTagline:\nBuilt to Scale. Designed to Last.\nPromise:\nWe turn operational chaos into competitive advantage.\nAudience:\nAmbitious founders and operators scaling \u00a31M\u2013\u00a310M businesses\n## Tone of Voice\nPrimary tone:\nAuthoritative but approachable. Expert, not arrogant.\nSecondary tone:\nPractical and action-oriented. We give people things they can use.\n## Language Rules\nDO use:\n- \"Operational clarity\" not \"getting organised\"\n- \"Scale\" not \"grow\" (growth is a by-product of scale)\n- \"Systems\" not \"processes\" (systems imply automation)\n- \"Operators\" not \"managers\" (operators execute, managers oversee)\nDO NOT use:\n- \"Synergy\", \"leverage\" (as a verb), \"circle back\", \"touch base\"\n- Exclamation marks in formal content\n- Passive voice (\"it was decided\" \u2192 \"we decided\")\n## Brand Colours (for reference in visual descriptions)\nPrimary:\n#C86B45 (FCO Copper)\nDark:\n#2F2E2D (FCO Charcoal)\nLight:\n#F6F5F2 (FCO Cream)\n# Workflow: Writing a Client Proposal\n## Purpose\nThis workflow defines how FCO writes proposals for new retainer clients.\nFollow this process exactly. Do not deviate.\n## Step 1: Discovery Summary\nBefore writing, confirm you have:\n- The client's primary pain point (in their words)\n- Their current situation and what has failed before\n- Their definition of success in 90 days\n- Their budget range and decision timeline\n## Step 2: Proposal Structure\nSection 1:\nThe Problem (mirror their language back to them)\nSection 2:\nWhy This Happens (show you understand the root cause)\nSection 3:\nOur Approach (3-phase methodology, not a list of deliverables)\nSection 4:\nWhat Success Looks Like (specific, measurable outcomes)\nSection 5:\nInvestment & Timeline\nSection 6:\nNext Steps (one clear action, not multiple options)\n## Rules\n- Maximum 4 pages. Founders do not read long proposals.\n- Lead with their problem, not our credentials.\n- Never use the word \"deliverables\" \u2014 use \"outcomes\" instead.\n- Every section should answer: \"So what does this mean for me?\"\n# Audience Profiles\n## Profile 1: The Scaling Founder\nName:\nAlex (composite)\nRevenue:\n\u00a32M\u2013\u00a35M, growing 30%+ year-on-year\nTeam:\n8\u201320 people, mostly hired reactively\nPain:\nEverything runs through them. They are the bottleneck.\nFear:\nHiring the wrong person and losing control of quality\nGoal:\nBuild a business that works without them in every decision\nReads:\nLenny's Newsletter, Diary of a CEO, First Class Operations\nResponds to:\nSpecificity, case studies, ROI framing, peer validation\n## Profile 2: The Operations Director\nName:\nSarah (composite)\nRevenue:\n\u00a35M\u2013\u00a315M business, hired to \"sort out the ops\"\nTeam:\nManages 3\u20135 direct reports, reports to CEO/Founder\nPain:\nNo documented processes, tribal knowledge, constant firefighting\nFear:\nBeing seen as the person who slows things down\nGoal:\nBuild credibility fast by delivering visible, measurable improvements\nResponds to:\nFrameworks, templates, quick wins, executive-ready reporting\n\ud83d\ude80\nThe Golden Prompt:\nOnce your files are in place, start every session with:\n\"Read the attached .md files completely before responding. DO NOT start executing yet. Ask me clarifying questions so we can align on the approach. Only begin work once we've agreed on the direction.\"\n\ud83d\udee0 Advanced Setup\nBuilding Your Own Skills Files\nA Skills file is a specialised context file that defines exactly how Claude should approach a specific type of task. Think of it as writing a job description for Claude \u2014 one that captures your methodology, your standards, and your non-negotiables.\n\ud83d\udca1\nWhy Skills Files Matter:\nA generic prompt produces generic output. A Skills file encodes your expertise \u2014 your frameworks, your quality standards, your decision rules \u2014 so Claude produces outputs that reflect your best thinking, not an average of the internet.\nThe Anatomy of a Skills File\n\ud83d\udcc4 Skills File Template\nCopy\n# SKILL: [Name of the Skill]\n# Version: 1.0\n# Use When: [Describe the exact situation where Claude should apply this skill]\n## PURPOSE\n[One sentence: what does this skill help Claude do?]\n## CONTEXT\n[Background information Claude needs to do this well. \nInclude relevant industry knowledge, your methodology, \nor any frameworks you use.]\n## PROCESS\nStep 1: [First action Claude should take]\nStep 2: [Second action]\nStep 3: [Continue as needed]\n## QUALITY STANDARDS\n- [Standard 1: e.g., \"Every recommendation must include a specific metric\"]\n- [Standard 2: e.g., \"Always present 3 options, not 1\"]\n- [Standard 3: e.g., \"Flag any assumption you are making\"]\n## OUTPUT FORMAT\n[Describe exactly how the output should be structured.\nHeaders, length, tone, format.]\n## RULES\n- [Non-negotiable rule 1]\n- [Non-negotiable rule 2]\n- NEVER [thing Claude must not do]\n- ALWAYS [thing Claude must always do]\n## EXAMPLES\n[Paste 1\u20132 examples of ideal outputs for this skill]\nReal Skills File Examples\n\ud83d\udcca\nskill_financial_analysis.md\nDefines how Claude should analyse financial data: what metrics to prioritise, how to flag anomalies, and how to present findings to a non-finance audience.\nUse When: Analysing P&L statements, cash flow reports, or budget variances for client review.\n\u270d\ufe0f\nskill_content_writing.md\nEncodes your writing style, structure preferences, and content rules so every piece of content sounds like it came from you \u2014 not a generic AI.\nUse When: Writing LinkedIn posts, newsletters, proposals, or any external-facing content.\n\ud83d\udd0d\nskill_client_research.md\nA structured research methodology for profiling prospects: what to look for, how to synthesise findings, and how to present intelligence for sales calls.\nUse When: Preparing for a new business meeting or building a competitive battlecard.\n\u2699\ufe0f\nskill_sop_creation.md\nDefines the exact structure and quality standards for Standard Operating Procedures: what sections to include, how to handle exceptions, and how to write for different audiences.\nUse When: Documenting any repeatable business process for a team member to follow.\n\ud83c\udfaf\nThe Compound Effect:\nEach Skills file you create makes Claude permanently better at that task. Start with your highest-frequency, highest-stakes work \u2014 the tasks you do every week that need to be consistently excellent. Build one Skills file per week for a month and you will have a custom AI system that reflects your expertise.\n\ud83d\udd25 Advanced Prompt\nTurn Claude Into Your Brutal Critic\nThe most valuable use of Claude for operators is not writing content \u2014 it is stress-testing your thinking. This prompt turns Claude into the advisor who tells you what you need to hear, not what you want to hear.\nStep 1\nWhat Are You Actually Saying?\nClaude reads between the lines. If you say \"I'm thinking about hiring,\" it identifies whether you're making a strategic move or avoiding a harder conversation.\nStep 2\nWhere Is Your Reasoning Broken?\nClaude dissects your logic like a mechanic taking apart an engine \u2014 showing you the specific part that doesn't work and why.\nStep 3\nWhat Are You Avoiding?\nEvery time you dodge something hard, there's a cost. Claude calculates it and shows you what another week of avoidance actually costs your business.\nStep 4\nWhat Would an Expert Do Differently?\nNot motivational \u2014 concrete. Claude shows you the specific gap between your current approach and what expert-level thinking looks like on the same problem.\nStep 5\nWhat Should You Actually Do?\nA precise, prioritised action plan. What to start, what to stop, and what evidence would tell you it is not working.\nStep 6\nThe Question You're Avoiding\nClaude ends with the one uncomfortable question you need to sit with \u2014 the one that makes your stomach drop a little.\n\ud83d\udd25 The Brutal Critic Prompt\nCopy\nYou are my brutally honest thinking partner. Your job is to make \nmy thinking sharper, my plans more realistic, and my blind spots \nvisible \u2014 every single time we talk.\nYou are not my cheerleader. You are not my yes-man. You're the \nadvisor who grabs my arm before I walk into a bad decision and \nsays \"Here's exactly why this is wrong.\"\nFor everything I share, do this:\n1. What am I actually saying vs. what I think I'm saying?\n2. Where is my reasoning broken? Show me the specific flaw.\n3. What am I avoiding, and what is it costing me?\n4. What would someone who's actually where I want to be do differently?\n5. What should I actually do \u2014 in order, starting now?\n6. What is the one question I'm clearly avoiding?\nRules:\n- Never open with praise or agreement. Ever.\n- Never soften a critique. Say the hard thing and let it land.\n- No motivational clich\u00e9s. Concrete language only.\n- Keep it tight. A short, precise hit lands harder than a lecture.\nI want to walk away from every conversation seeing something \nI couldn't see before \u2014 even if it stings.\n\u2696 Context\nClaude vs. The Alternatives\nNo tool is best at everything. Here is an honest assessment of where Claude wins, where it falls short, and which tools to use for the gaps.\nTask\nClaude\nChatGPT\nGemini\nGrok\nLong-form writing & strategy\n\u2713 Best\n~ Good\n~ Good\n\u2717 Weak\nComplex reasoning & analysis\n\u2713 Best\n~ Good\n~ Good\n\u2717 Weak\nWorking with your files (Cowork)\n\u2713 Best\n~ Limited\n\u2717 No\n\u2717 No\nExcel / spreadsheet integration\n\u2713 Best\n\u2717 Flattens data\n\u2717 No\n\u2717 No\nReal-time web search\n~ Limited\n~ Good\n~ Good\n\u2713 Best (X data)\nImage generation\n\u2717 None\n\u2713 DALL-E\n\u2713 Best\n\u2717 No\nVideo generation\n\u2717 None\n\u2717 No\n\u2713 VEO\n\u2717 No\nCode generation\n\u2713 Excellent\n\u2713 Excellent\n~ Good\n~ Good\n\ud83c\udfaf\nThe FCO Stack:\nUse Claude for everything that requires thinking, writing, and working with your data. Use Gemini for image generation. Use Grok for real-time news and social intelligence. These three tools cover 95% of what a modern operator needs.\n\ud83d\udcbc Real-World Impact\nWhat Operators Actually Use Claude For\nThese are the highest-value use cases from operators who have embedded Claude into their daily work. Each one includes the exact prompt structure that works \u2014 not a vague suggestion, but a template you can use today.\n\ud83d\udcdd\nSOP Documentation\nTurn rough process notes into a complete, formatted SOP with decision trees and exception handling \u2014 in under 10 minutes.\n\"Read my notes on [process]. Build a full SOP with a decision tree for edge cases. Ask me questions before you start.\"\n\ud83d\udcc8\nQuarterly Business Reviews\nUpload raw data and get a structured QBR narrative ready for the leadership team \u2014 with wins, risks, and recommendations.\n\"Read the Q[X] data files. Draft a QBR narrative for the leadership team. Highlight the 3 biggest wins and 2 critical risks.\"\n\ud83e\udd1d\nProposal Writing\nFeed Claude your brand voice, past proposals, and the client brief. Get a proposal that sounds like your best work \u2014 not a template.\n\"Using my brand voice file and the client brief, write a proposal for this project. Match my tone exactly. Ask clarifying questions first.\"\n\ud83d\udd0d\nCompetitive Intelligence\nFeed Claude competitor data, market reports, and your positioning doc to get a strategic gap analysis with clear differentiators.\n\"Analyse these competitor profiles against our positioning. Identify our 3 strongest differentiators and 2 areas of vulnerability.\"\n\ud83d\udce7\nHigh-Stakes Email Drafting\nGive Claude the context, the relationship history, and the outcome you need. Get a draft that is precise, on-tone, and ready to send.\n\"I need to write to [person] about [situation]. Context: [background]. Goal: [outcome]. Draft this email in my voice. Ask questions first.\"\n\ud83e\udde0\nStrategic Decision Review\nBefore making a major decision, run it through the Brutal Critic prompt. Claude will find the flaws in your thinking before you commit.\n\"I'm considering [decision]. Read my reasoning below. Tell me where my logic is broken, what I'm avoiding, and what I should actually do.\"\n\ud83d\udcca\nFinancial Model Building\nBuild a complete, formula-driven financial model in Excel from a plain-English brief \u2014 with assumptions tab, dashboard, and trend charts.\n\"Build a 3-year P&L model for a service business with 40% gross margins. Use formulas, not hardcoded numbers. Put assumptions in their own tab.\"\n\ud83c\udfaf\nClient Onboarding Packs\nUpload your methodology, the client's brief, and their discovery notes. Claude builds a complete onboarding pack tailored to their situation.\n\"Using the discovery notes and our methodology doc, build a complete onboarding pack for [Client]. Include a 90-day roadmap and success metrics.\"\n\ud83d\udce3\nContent & Newsletter Writing\nFeed Claude your writing samples and a topic. Get a first draft that matches your voice, structure, and standards \u2014 ready to edit, not rewrite.\n\"Using my writing samples file, write a LinkedIn post about [topic]. Target [audience]. Goal: [outcome]. Match my tone and structure exactly.\"\n\ud83d\udd11\nThe pattern behind every great use case:\nContext file loaded + alignment prompt used + specific outcome defined. That three-part structure is what separates operators who get 10\u00d7 output from those who get generic answers. Every prompt above follows it.\n\ud83d\udcc4 Step-by-Step Guide\nHow to Build Your MD & Skills Files From Scratch\nA Markdown (.md) file is a plain text file with simple formatting. You do not need any special software. You need a text editor, 20 minutes, and the templates below. Here is the exact process for building every file type.\nStep 1: Create the File\nOpen\nNotepad\n(Windows),\nTextEdit\n(Mac, in plain text mode), or\nVS Code\n(recommended \u2014 free).\nWrite your content using the templates below. Use\n#\nfor headings,\n##\nfor sub-headings, and plain text for content.\nSave the file with a\n.md extension\n\u2014 e.g.,\nabout.md\n,\nbrand.md\n.\nCreate a dedicated folder on your computer called\nClaude Context\nand store all your .md files there.\nIn Claude Cowork, point the folder selector at your\nClaude Context\nfolder. Claude will read every file in it automatically.\n\ud83d\udca1\nOr use the AI File Generator:\nSkip the blank page entirely. Our\ninteractive agent\nasks you the right questions and builds your files automatically \u2014 ready to download and use.\nStep 2: Name Your Files Correctly\nConsistent naming makes it easy to reference files in prompts and keeps your folder organised as it grows.\nFile Name\nWhat It Contains\nabout.md\nYour role, goals, communication style, writing examples\nbrand.md\nTone of voice, language rules, values, audience\nworkflow_[name].md\nStep-by-step process for a specific task type\nskill_[name].md\nDomain expertise + quality standards for a task type\nreference_data.md\nPricing, metrics, product specs, key numbers\naudience_profiles.md\nClient/customer profiles, pain points, goals\nStep 3: What to Write in Each File\nThe quality of your output is directly proportional to the quality of your context files. Here is what to include in each one \u2014 and what most people miss.\n\ud83d\udc64\nabout.md \u2014 The Foundation\nMost people write a job description. Write a\nbrief\ninstead \u2014 as if you're onboarding a new team member who needs to think like you.\nYour role and what you're responsible for\nWhat success looks like in your world\nHow you communicate (tone, format, pace)\nWords/phrases you use and avoid\n2\u20133 examples of writing you're proud of\nYour current top 3 priorities\n\ud83c\udfa8\nbrand.md \u2014 The Voice\nThis is the file that makes Claude sound like\nyou\n, not like a generic AI. Be specific \u2014 vague instructions produce vague outputs.\nBrand positioning in one sentence\nPrimary and secondary tone descriptors\nSpecific words you DO use (with examples)\nSpecific words you DO NOT use\nFormatting rules (headers, bullets, length)\nTarget audience description\n\u2699\ufe0f\nskill_[name].md \u2014 The Expertise\nThis is where you encode your methodology. Think of it as writing the instructions for a highly capable contractor who knows nothing about your standards.\nWhen to use this skill (trigger conditions)\nYour step-by-step process\nQuality standards and non-negotiables\nOutput format and structure\nRules: what to always do / never do\n1\u20132 examples of ideal output\n\u26a1 Skip the Blank Page\nUse the AI File Generator\nAnswer a few questions about your business and role. The agent builds all your context and skills files automatically \u2014 ready to download and load into Claude.\nBuild My Files Now \u2192\n\ud83d\ude80 Your Action Plan\nMaster Claude in 30 Minutes\nBlock 30 minutes this week. Follow this plan in order. By the end, you will have a working Claude setup that is personalised to your business and ready to use every day.\n1\nMinutes 0\u20135\nInstall Claude & Get Pro\nDownload the desktop app from claude.com/download. Create an account or sign in. Upgrade to Pro ($20/month or $17/month annually). Open the app and click the Cowork tab.\n\u2192 claude.com/download\n2\nMinutes 5\u201312\nCreate Your First Context File\nOpen any text editor. Create a file called\nabout.md\n. Write three things: (1) what you do for work, (2) how you like to communicate, (3) paste in one example of writing you're proud of. Save it as a .md file.\n\u2192 Use the template in the Context Files section above\n3\nMinutes 12\u201318\nStart Your First Cowork Conversation\nIn Claude Cowork, select the folder where your about.md file lives. Use the Alignment Prompt: \"Read the about-me file. Based on it, ask me questions before drafting [your most important current task].\" See what happens. Iterate.\n\u2192 Use the Alignment Prompt from Tool 1 above\n4\nMinutes 18\u201323\nInstall a Plugin & Try a Slash Command\nGo to claude.com/plugins. Install the plugin most relevant to your role (Marketing, Sales, or Data are good starting points). Start a new Cowork conversation with the plugin active. Type / to see available commands and try one.\n\u2192 claude.com/plugins\n5\nMinutes 23\u201327\nBuild Your First Artifact\nInside any Claude chat, ask it to build something interactive: \"Create a weekly capacity planner as an interactive HTML page with team member rows and colour-coded utilisation.\" Interact with it. Ask for changes. Download it.\n\u2192 Use the Artifact prompts from Tool 5 above\n6\nMinutes 27\u201330\nInstall Claude in Excel\nOpen Excel. Go to Insert \u2192 Get Add-ins. Search \"Claude by Anthropic.\" Install. Open any spreadsheet and ask: \"Give me a plain-English summary of what each tab does.\" Or start a new financial model from scratch using the prompt in Tool 3.\n\u2192 Use the Excel prompts from Tool 3 above\nHelping ambitious founders and operators build the systems they need to scale without chaos.\nThis Guide\nThe Six Tools\nDeep Dives\nContext Files\nSkills Files\n30-Min Action Plan\nFirst Class Operations\nAbout FCO\nAI Masterclass\nOperations Consulting\nContact\n\u00a9 2026 First Class Operations. All rights reserved.\nBuilt for operators who demand\nfirst class execution\n.\n\u2191";
